[1]
Date: 16 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NY Times [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/national/AP-Salmonella-Outbreak.html>

More Pennsylvania salmonella cases linked to chain
---------------------------------------------
More than 60 cases of salmonella poisoning have now been traced to a
convenience store chain where people ate, prompting a food supplier to
quarantine some of its inventory, authorities said Thu 15 Jul 2004.
Health officials initially traced 34 cases of salmonella poisoning,
throughout western Pennsylvania, to Sheetz stores, which has pulled the
lettuce and Roma tomatoes suspected of causing the illness.
The Altoona-based chain also switched produce suppliers, and disinfected
its sandwich counters, at more than 300 stores in Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia, and North Carolina.
Coronet Foods, of Wheeling, W.Va., which supplies produce to Sheetz, said
it had stopped buying and processing Roma tomatoes pending its own
investigation. The company also quarantined its remaining inventory,
reorganized the tomato processing line, and notified growers and suppliers.
In a statement, Coronet officials noted that sliced Roma tomatoes make up 1
percent of their line, and, most of it is distributed to Sheetz.
The Pennsylvania Agriculture Department was testing food samples Thu 15 Jul
2004 to confirm the presence and type of salmonella bacteria.
Salmonella bacteria can contaminate food or water, and those who are
infected by it generally suffer from diarrhea, fever, and cramps for up to
3 days. It can be fatal in rare cases.
Health officials said, on Thu 15 Jul 2004, that there were more than 60
confirmed cases (50 in 12 Pennsylvania counties). In Maryland, public
health officials confirmed at least 14 cases; West Virginia had one
confirmed case.
Ohio health officials were unaware of any cases linked to the convenience
stores. But, the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said
there were an unspecified number of cases in Ohio involving people who ate
at Sheetz stores.
Sheetz officials did not immediately return calls on Thu 15 Jul 2004.
