[We, perhaps, have prematurely labeled this thread as "tomatoes,
convenience stores," before the actual etiology has been confirmed. As
there is still a high-likelihood of involvement, rather than add ":NOT" to
the thread, we shall continue this title, pending firm confirmation. While
tomatoes have not frequently been associated with salmonella transmission,
there was the earlier outbreak of _Salmonella javiana_ associated with Roma
tomatoes in 2002 (see references below).
As the 3rd article correctly states, the absence of identification of the
organism in the food samples does not rule out the possibility that earlier
batches of the food items were responsible for this outbreak. If all
specimens are negative, the epidemiological investigations may be the only
source of information for identifying the most likely source for the
outbreak. Obviously, it is "neater" if one can actually culture the
organisms from the implicated food(s), but, sometimes it remains as
"implicated" by virtue of the epidemiological investigation. Remember, John
Snow did implicate the Broad Street pump as the source of infection in the
cholera outbreak in London in the pre-Moore swab and bacterial culturing
days. We await further information on the final results of the laboratory
testing. - Mod.MPP]
